Exploratory data analysis¶

Exploratory data analysis is the method of examining data and extracting findings. It's fiction, a storyline that data is attempting to convey. EDA is a way of analyzing data using a variety of tools and graphical approaches such as matplotlib, charts, heatmap, scatterplots and seaborn. The first phase in the data modelling process is often EDA. We can ask to define the objectives or statement on our data set through the EDA procedure, which is very essential. It is a good idea to first know the statistics and then attempt to extract as many conclusions as possible. EDA is all about understanding the meaning of it. In this tutorial, we will show you how to use all of the above tools to efficiently investigate your data so that you can begin analyzing it. This part will explain what Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) is and what the difference between EDA and Data Mining is. We will follow some steps to get insights of the dataset that includes :

  • Getting some descriptive analysis of the dataset which includes, finding missing or null values, duplicate values.
  • Dealing with the null values
  • Univariate and bivariate analysis of the dataset.
  • Splitting the data into x and y for data modeling and predictive analysis

Univariate Analysis¶

Univariate analysis is the most fundamental type of data analysis. Uni signifies "one," implying that the data contains only one type of variable. The primary goal of univariate analysis is to characterise the data. The data will be gathered, summarised, and a pattern will be discovered. Univariate analysis can be done in a variety of ways, the majority of which are descriptive in nature. These ways are Histograms, Bar Charts, Pie Charts, The Frequency Distribution Tables, Frequency Polygons.

Hypothesis testing¶

Hypothesis testing is a statistical strategy for making statistical conclusions based on data from experiments. Hypothesis testing is essentially making an assumption about a parameter. A hypothesis test compares necessarily related distinct assumptions about a group to see which one the sample data best supports. A hypothesis test is used to determine whether a result is statistically significant. The null hypothesis is a general definition or baseline assumption in hypothesis testing that there is no relationship between two measurable events or no connection among categories. To put it another way, it's a fundamental assumption based on domain or problem information.
The alternative hypothesis is a hypothesis that opposes the null hypothesis and is used in hypothesis testing. The observations are usually assumed to be the consequence of a true effect with some random fluctuation superposed.

Paired sampled t-test¶

The dependent sample t-test is another name for the paired sample t-test. It's only one experiment that looks for a statistically significant difference between two related variables.
We are going to perform paired sample t-test on our dataset which includes 2PA and 3PA columns.

In [32]:
test,p_Val = stats.ttest_rel(df['2PA'], df['3PA'])
print(p_Val)
if p_Val<0.05:
    print("We Reject null hypothesis")
else:
    print("accept null hypothesis")

6.261831927615957e-07
We Reject null hypothesis

From the results we have found that our p value is lesser than 0.05 and we reject the null hypothesis. The next step will be implementing the machine learning and making predicitions about the data.

Machine Learning¶

Advancing K-means cluster into our dataset¶

The three types of learning in Machine Learning can be broadly characterised as follows: Supervised learning, unsupervised learning, and semi-supervised learning are the three types of learning. Unsupervised Learning algorithms do not have any variables to predict that are related to the data. Rather than just an outcome, the data has only an intake, which is a set of numerous variables that characterise the data.
Clustering is the challenge of arranging a collection of objects so that objects in the same group are more similar than objects in other groups. Correlation is an indicator that shows how closely two data objects are related. Clustering is mostly employed in exploratory data analysis.
Machine learning, problem solving, computer vision, data mining, informatics, image segmentation, and image processing are just a few of the domains where it's used.
K-Means is a type of centroid-based clustering algorithm. A centroid is a data point in the centre of a cluster (imaginary or actual). Clusters are represented by a central vector or a centroid in centroid-based clustering. This centroid may or may not be a part of the dataset. K - means clustering is an adaptive technique that determines similarity by how close a data point is to the cluster's centroid.
You use the distance measurement function (also known as the similarity measurement function) to measure the distances:
$ d=\left | x2 - x1 \right | + \left | y2 - y1 \right |+ \left | z2-z1 \right |\ $

In [33]:
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2)
kmeans.fit(df.drop('MinutesPercentage',axis=1))

Important predictive analytics such as recall, specificity, accuracy, and precision are visualised using confusion matrices. Confusion matrices are important because they allow you to compare values such as True Positives, False Positives, True Negatives, and False Negatives in a straightforward manner.
Other machine learning classification measures, such as "Accuracy," on the other hand, provide less valuable data because Accuracy is simply the difference between correct and incorrect predictions divided by the total number of predictions.

In [37]:

  • Precision Precision is interested in how many genuinely positive cases your model detected out of all the positive examples it tagged. It's the number of genuine positives divided by total of positive class + false positives.

  • Recall The percentage of positive examples that your model was able to recognise from the whole set of positive examples is known as recall. The hit rate is also known as recall, while tolerance refers to a model's genuine positive modeling level or recall chance.

The elbow approach is a heuristic used in cluster analysis to determine the number of clusters in a data set. Selecting the elbow of the curve as the number of clusters to utilise and plotting the explained variation as a function of the number of clusters is what this approach does.

In [44]:
m = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, init='k-means++', max_iter=300, n_init=10, random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(df.drop('MinutesPercentage',axis=1))
    m.append(kmeans.inertia_)
plt.plot(range(1, 11), m)
plt.title('Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Numbers/Range')
plt.show()

Mostly the number of clusters lies for having higher values of the inertia
